[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] It’s been available across browsers since September 2020.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] The **`Intl.Locale`** object is a standard built-in property of the Intl object that represents a Unicode locale identifier.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] The **`Intl.Locale`** object was created to allow for easier manipulation of Unicode locales.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Unicode represents locales with a string, called a *locale identifier*.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] The locale identifier consists of a *language identifier* and *extension tags*.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Language identifiers are the core of the locale, consisting of *language*, *script*, *region*, and *variants* subtags.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Additional information about the locale is stored in the optional *extension tags*.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Extension tags hold information about locale aspects such as calendar type, clock type, and numbering system type.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Traditionally, the Intl API used strings to represent locales, just as Unicode does.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] This is a simple and lightweight solution that works well.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Adding a Locale class, however, adds ease of parsing and manipulating the language, script, and region, as well as extension tags.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] The information above is exactly provided as-is when the `Locale` object is constructed, without consulting any external database.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] The `Intl.Locale` object additionally provides some methods that return information about the locale's real-world information, such as available calendars, collations, and numbering systems.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] These properties are defined on `Intl.Locale.prototype` and shared by all `Intl.Locale` instances.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns basic, core information about the `Locale` in the form of a substring of the complete data string.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns the part of the `Locale` that indicates the Locale's calendar era.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns whether case is taken into account for the locale's collation rules.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns the collation type for the `Locale`, which is used to order strings according to the locale's rules.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] The constructor function that created the instance object.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] For `Intl.Locale` instances, the initial value is the `Intl.Locale` constructor.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns the time keeping format convention used by the locale.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns the language associated with the locale.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns the numeral system used by the locale.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns whether the locale has special collation handling for numeric characters.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns the region of the world (usually a country) associated with the locale.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns the script used for writing the particular language used in the locale.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns the variants subtags (such as different orthographies) associated with the locale.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Intl.Locale"`.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns an `Array` of available calendar identifiers, according to the locale's rules.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns an `Array` of the collation types for the `Locale`.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns an `Array` of hour cycle identifiers, indicating either the 12-hour clock ("h12"), the Japanese 12-hour clock ("h11"), the 24-hour clock ("h23"), or the unused format "h24".
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns an `Array` of numbering system identifiers available according to the locale's rules.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns the part indicating the ordering of characters `ltr` (left-to-right) or `rtl` (right-to-left).
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns an `Array` of time zone identifiers, associated with the `Locale`.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns UTS 35's Week Elements according to the locale rules.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Gets the most likely values for the language, script, and region of the locale based on existing values.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Attempts to remove information about the locale that would be added by calling `maximize()`.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] Returns the Locale's full locale identifier string.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-locale] The constructor also takes an optional configuration object argument, which can contain any of several extension types.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] It’s been available across browsers since September 2019.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] The **`Intl.PluralRules`** object enables plural-sensitive formatting and plural-related language rules.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] Languages use different patterns for expressing both plural numbers of items (cardinal numbers) and for expressing the order of items (ordinal numbers).
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] English has two forms for expressing cardinal numbers: one for the singular "item" (1 hour, 1 dog, 1 fish) and the other for zero or any other number of "items" (0 hours, 2 lemmings, 100000.5 fish), while Chinese has only one form, and Arabic has six!
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] Similarly, English has four forms for expressing ordinal numbers: "th", "st", "nd", "rd", giving the sequence: 0th, 1st, 2nd, 3rd, 4th, 5th, ..., 21st, 22nd, 23rd, 24th, 25th, and so on, while both Chinese and Arabic only have one form for ordinal numbers.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] Given a particular language and set of formatting options, the methods `Intl.PluralRules.prototype.select()` and `Intl.PluralRules.prototype.selectRange()` return a *tag* that represents the plural form of a single or a range of numbers, cardinal or ordinal.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] Code can use the returned tags to represent numbers appropriately for the given language.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] The full set of tags that might be returned are: `zero`, `one`, `two`, `few`, `many`, and `other` (the "general" plural form, also used if the language only has one form).
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] As English only has two forms for cardinal numbers, the `select()` method returns only two tags: `"one"` for the singular case, and `"other"` for all other cardinal numbers.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] This allows construction of sentences that make sense in English for each case, such as: "1 dog is happy; do you want to play with it?" and "10 dogs are happy; do you want to play with them?".
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] Creating appropriate sentences for each form depends on the language, and even in English may not be as simple as just adding "s" to a noun to make the plural form.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] Other languages have more forms, and choosing appropriate sentences can be even more complex.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] `select()` can return any of four tags for ordinal numbers in English, representing each of the allowed forms: `one` for "st" numbers (1, 21, 31, ...), `two` for "nd" numbers (2, 22, 32, ...), `few` for "rd" numbers (3, 33, 43, ...), and `other` for "th" numbers (0, 4-20, etc.).
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] Again, the returned tags allow appropriate formatting of strings describing an ordinal number.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] For more information about the rules and how they are used, see Plural Rules.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] For a list of the rules and how they apply for different languages, see the LDML Language Plural Rules.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] Creates a new `Intl.PluralRules` object.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] Returns an array containing those of the provided locales that are supported without having to fall back to the runtime's default locale.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] These properties are defined on `Intl.PluralRules.prototype` and shared by all `Intl.PluralRules` instances.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] For `Intl.PluralRules` instances, the initial value is the `Intl.PluralRules` constructor.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Intl.PluralRules"`.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] Returns a new object with properties reflecting the locale and collation options computed during initialization of the object.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] Returns a string indicating which plural rule to use for locale-aware formatting.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] This method receives two values and returns a string indicating which plural rule to use for locale-aware formatting.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] This example shows some of the variations in localized plural rules for cardinal numbers.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] The plural form of the specified number may also depend on constructor `options`, such as how the number is rounded, and whether it is cardinal or ordinal.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] This example shows how you can set the type of rules to "ordinal", and how this affects the form for some numbers in US English.
[src:localization-i18n/intl-pluralrules] The code below extends the previous example, showing how you might use the returned tag for an ordinal number to format text in English.
[src:localization-i18n/language-code] A **language code** is a code that assigns letters or numbers as identifiers or classifiers for languages.
[src:localization-i18n/language-code] These codes may be used to organize library collections or presentations of data, to choose the correct localizations and translations in computing, and as a shorthand designation for longer forms of language names.
[src:localization-i18n/language-code] Language code schemes attempt to classify the complex world of human languages, dialects, and variants.
[src:localization-i18n/language-code] Most schemes make some compromises between being general and being complete enough to support specific dialects.
[src:localization-i18n/language-code] For example, Spanish is spoken in over 20 countries in North America, Central America, the Caribbean, and Europe.
[src:localization-i18n/language-code] Spanish spoken in Mexico will be slightly different from Spanish spoken in Peru.
[src:localization-i18n/language-code] Different regions of Mexico will have slightly different dialects and accents of Spanish.
[src:localization-i18n/language-code] A language code scheme might group these all as "Spanish" for choosing a keyboard layout, most as "Spanish" for general usage, or separate each dialect to allow region-specific variation.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Language localisation differs from translation activity because it involves a comprehensive study of the target culture in order to correctly adapt the product to local needs.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Localisation can be referred to by the numeronym **L10N** (as in: "L", followed by the number 10, and then "N").
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Localisation can be done for regions or countries where people speak different languages or where the same language is spoken.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] For instance, different dialects of German, with different idioms, are spoken in Germany, Austria, Switzerland, and Belgium.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] The former Localization Industry Standards Association (LISA) said that **globalisation** "can best be thought of as a cycle rather than a single process".
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] To *globalise* is to plan the design and development methods for a product in advance, keeping in mind a multicultural audience, in order to avoid increased costs and quality problems, save time, and smooth the localising effort for each region or country.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] There are two primary technical processes that comprise globalisation: internationalisation and localisation.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] The first phase, **internationalisation**, encompasses the planning and preparation stages for a product built to support global markets.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] This process removes all cultural assumptions, and country- or language-specific content is stored so that it can be easily adapted.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] If this content is not separated during this phase, it must be fixed during localisation, adding time and expense to the project.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] In extreme cases, products that are not internationalised may not be localisable.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Internationalization is often written as 'i18n' in the localization industry, where the number 18 is the number of letters between i and n in the English word.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] The second phase, **localisation**, refers to the actual adaptation of the product for a specific market.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] The localisation phase involves, among other things, the four issues LISA describes as *linguistic*, *physical*, *business and cultural*, and *technical* issues.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Localization is sometimes written as 'l10n', where the number 10 refers to the number of letters between l and n.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] At the end of each phase, testing (including quality assurance) is performed to ensure that the product works properly and meets the client's quality expectations.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Though it is sometimes difficult to draw the limits between translation and localisation, in general localisation addresses significant, non-textual components of products or services.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] All these changes aim to recognise local sensitivities; avoid conflict with local culture, customs, and common habits; and enter the local market by merging into its needs and desires.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] To sum up, localisation always starts with a translation process followed by adaptations regarding linguistic and cultural factors.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] For example, localisation aims to offer country-specific websites of the same company or different editions of a book depending on where it is published.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] For instance, Japan's national language is Japanese and is the primary language for over 99% of the population, but the country also recognises 11 languages officially; others are spoken by transient populations, and others yet are spoken as second or other languages.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Whereas localisation is the process of adapting one product to a particular locale, globalisation designs the product to minimise the extra work required for each localisation.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Suppose that a company operating exclusively in Germany chooses to open a major office in Russia and needs a Russian-language website.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] The company offers the same products and services in both countries with minor differences, but perhaps some elements that appeared in the original website intended for a German audience are offensive or upsetting in Russia (use of flags, colours, nationalistic images, songs, etc.).
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Thus, that company might lose a potential market because of small details of presentation.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Furthermore, this company might need to adapt the product to its new buyers; video games are the best example.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Now, suppose instead that this company has major offices in a dozen countries and needs a specifically designed website in each of these countries.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Before deciding how to localise the website and the products offered in any given country, a professional in the area might advise the company to create an overall strategy: to globalise the way the organisation does business.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] The company might want to design a framework to codify and support this global strategy.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] The globalisation strategy and the globalisation framework would provide uniform guidance for the twelve separate localisation efforts.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Globalisation is especially important in mitigating extra work involved in the long-term cycle of localisation.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Because localisation is usually a cycle and not a one-time project, there are new texts, updates, and projects to localise.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] For example, as the original website is updated over time, each already translated and localised website must be updated.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] This work cycle is continuous as long as the original project continues to evolve.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] A streamlined globalisation processes is therefore important for ongoing changes.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] The use of technology has developed into an important aspect of translation and localization.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] The industry now holds a strong preference for the use of technology in the translation, editing, and proofreading process as it provides major benefits in project management workflow automation, terminology consistency, quality assurance.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] A Translation Management System (TMS) is a software program that supports the organization and facilitation of translation and localisation projects.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] A localisation project usually involves multiple individuals often located in different locales, this makes the TMS a necessary tool in piecing together everyone's efforts.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] The TMS provides organization and automation to the project management workflow, collects project data, generates reports, and integrates necessary elements such as machine translation (MT), translation memory (TM), and sometimes provides access to quality assurance tools.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] In essence, the TMS provides a workbench for all the necessary tools involved in a successful translation and localization operation.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Language codes are closely related to the localising process because they indicate the locales involved in the translation and adaptation of the product.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] They are used in various contexts; for example, they might be informally used in a document published by the European Union or they might be introduced in HTML element under the lang attribute.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] In the case of the European Union style guide, the language codes are based on the ISO 639-1 alpha-2 code; in HTML, the language tags are generally defined within the Internet Engineering Task Force's *Best Current Practice* (BCP) 47.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] The decision to use one type of code or tag versus another depends upon the nature of the project and any requirements set out for the localisation specialist.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Most frequently, there is a primary subcode that identifies the language (e.g., "en"), and an optional subcode in capital letters that specifies the national variety (e.g., "GB" or "US" according to ISO 3166-1 alpha-2).
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] The subcodes are typically linked with a hyphen, though in some contexts it's necessary to substitute this with an underscore.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] There are multiple language tag systems available for language codification.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] For example, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) specifies both two- and three-letter codes to represent languages in standards ISO 639-1 and ISO 639-2, respectively.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Localisation started mainly as manual translation and content adaptation for software and documentation.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Projects were labor-intensive with basic translation workflows and no formalized industry roles.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Early work was done by translators and engineers pieced together on a case-by-case basis.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] International software companies began setting up in-house localisation teams to adapt products for non-home markets, still with heavy human effort.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] As translation studies began to intersect with technical localisation, scholarly work helped define software localisation, web localisation, and later, multimedia and game localisation as distinct areas of practice.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Dedicated roles such as project managers and localisation engineers emerged to handle workflow coordination and technical adaptation of software strings.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] With globalization accelerating, professional translation and localisation services scaled up.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Tools like translation memory and early TMS systems started shaping new specialist roles.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Localisation teams grew to include roles that bridged linguistic, cultural, technical, and project work.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Modern roles now incorporate technology: AI/ML-assisted translation, automation, and continuous localization workflows.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] Strategic roles (e.g., Directors of International Product, Heads of Globalization) tie localization directly to business goals, not just translation output.
[src:localization-i18n/language-localisation] This is noted transition from previous functions in the industry.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] These specific alterations make the original words appear readable, but include the most problematic characteristics of the world's languages: varying length of text or characters, language direction, fit into the interface and so on.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] Traditionally, localization of software is independent of the software development process.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] In a typical scenario, software would be built and tested in one base language (such as English), with any *localizable* elements being extracted into external resources.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] Those resources are handed off to a localization team for translation into different target languages.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] The problem with this approach is that many subtle software bugs may be found during the process of localization, when it is too late (or more likely, too expensive) to fix them.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] The types of problems that can arise during localization involve differences in how written text appears in different languages.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] In addition, the localization process may uncover places where an element should be localizable, but is hard coded in a source language.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] This is why pseudolocalisation is to be considered an engineering or internationalization tool more than a localization one.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] Although the pseudolocalization technique has been used at Microsoft since the late 90s, it was made available to developers as a feature to test their program with different dialects during the cycle development of Windows Vista.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] The type of pseudo-language invented for this purpose is called a **pseudo locale** in Windows parlance.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] These locales were designed to use character sets and scripts characteristics from one of the three broad classes of foreign languages used by Windows at the time—basic ("Western"), mirrored ("Near-Eastern"), and CJK ("Far-Eastern").
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] This process produces translated strings that are longer, include non-ASCII characters, and (in the case of the "mirrored" pseudo-locale), are written right-to-left.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] One of the key features of the pseudolocalization process is that it happens automatically, during the development cycle, as part of a routine build.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] The process is almost identical to the process used to produce true localized builds, but is done *before* a build is tested, much earlier in the development cycle.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] This leaves time for any bugs that are found to be fixed in the base code, which is much easier than bugs not found until a release date is near.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] The builds that are produced by the pseudolocalization process are tested using the same QA cycle as a non-localized build.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] Since the pseudo-locales are mimicking English text, they can be tested by an English speaker.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] Beta version of Windows (7 and 8) have been released with some pseudo-localized strings intact.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] For these recent version of Windows, the pseudo-localized build is the primary staging build (the one created routinely for testing), and the final English language build is a "localized" version of that.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] Besides the tools used internally by Microsoft, other internationalization tools now include pseudolocalization options.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] These tools include Alchemy Catalyst from Alchemy Software Development, SDL Passolo from SDL and Globalyst from g11n.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] Such tools include pseudo-localization capability, including ability to view rendered Pseudo-localized dialogs and automating the testing process itself.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] While tools like Globalyst complete the whole process of creating pseudolocalised build and automate the testing, it can also be done by running a custom made pseudolocalization script on the extracted text resources and manually testing it.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] There are a variety of free pseudolocalization resources on the Internet that will create pseudolocalized versions of common localization formats like iOS strings, Android xml, Gettext po, and others.
[src:localization-i18n/pseudolocalization] These sites allow developers to upload strings file to a Web site and download the resulting pseudolocalized file.
[src:localization-i18n/relativetimeformat] The **`Intl.RelativeTimeFormat`** object enables language-sensitive relative time formatting.
[src:localization-i18n/relativetimeformat] Creates a new `Intl.RelativeTimeFormat` object.
[src:localization-i18n/relativetimeformat] These properties are defined on `Intl.RelativeTimeFormat.prototype` and shared by all `Intl.RelativeTimeFormat` instances.
[src:localization-i18n/relativetimeformat] For `Intl.RelativeTimeFormat` instances, the initial value is the `Intl.RelativeTimeFormat` constructor.
[src:localization-i18n/relativetimeformat] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Intl.RelativeTimeFormat"`.
[src:localization-i18n/relativetimeformat] Formats a `value` and a `unit` according to the locale and formatting options of the given `Intl.RelativeTimeFormat` object.
[src:localization-i18n/relativetimeformat] Returns an `Array` of objects representing the relative time format in parts that can be used for custom locale-aware formatting.
[src:localization-i18n/relativetimeformat] Returns a new object with properties reflecting the locale and formatting options computed during initialization of the object.
[src:localization-i18n/relativetimeformat] The following example shows how to use a relative time formatter for the English language.
[src:localization-i18n/relativetimeformat] The following example shows how to create a relative time formatter returning formatted parts.
